The President issued a statement expressing his satisfaction with the passage of trade agreements and trade adjustment assistance. He believes that these agreements with South Korea, Colombia, and Panama will benefit American workers and businesses. The President has advocated for the best possible deal for the United States and has also emphasized the need to support American workers affected by global competition. The bipartisan support for the agreements is seen as a significant achievement. The President expects that the agreements will boost exports, create more American jobs, and protect labor rights, the environment, and intellectual property. He believes that American automakers, farmers, ranchers, manufacturers, and small businesses will be able to compete and succeed in new markets. The President looks forward to signing these agreements as part of his goal to double American exports and maintain competitiveness in the 21st century.